snippet.textDisplay: Should first watch Ivan Miranda's series on 3D printing a screw drive vehicle. And watch every other video on these sorts of vehicles, which go back to at least the 1920's. Colin has already set his up to fail. The screw cylinders are too small diameter and the driving threads are way too tall, and they're uneven. Look up the old Fordson tractor video and how it easily cruises around in deep snow using large (high flotation) cylinders with a quite shallow thread depth. What ought to work best on Colin's cylinders is wrapping two spirals of steel rod around the cylinders. REDNIC79 built similar vehicle on YouTube back in 2016. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_bHUlJAaE2s
snippet.textOriginal: Should first watch Ivan Miranda's series on 3D printing a screw drive vehicle. And watch every other video on these sorts of vehicles, which go back to at least the 1920's. Colin has already set his up to fail. The screw cylinders are too small diameter and the driving threads are way too tall, and they're uneven. Look up the old Fordson tractor video and how it easily cruises around in deep snow using large (high flotation) cylinders with a quite shallow thread depth. What ought to work best on Colin's cylinders is wrapping two spirals of steel rod around the cylinders. snippet.textDisplay: World of Tanks is a game in which developers are making everything to get players pay money, although the game is free on the surface. And prices of assets in game are just ridiculously high. You can buy several good games for the price of one premium tank in WOT. And if you take two similar players, the one who spends money on in game assets will win. Quickly this becomes really frustrating.
